{"key":"processedPost-13523212","value":{"id":13523212,"first":13522899,"last":13580724,"when":1290441409,"utime":"11/22/10 05:56 PM","content":"<blockquote>Quote:<br />I'm pretty sure FAE in this setup isn't a prob, Coolmist running 24/7 with the ultrasonic dial currently on 100%, planning to turn that down once pin formation is visible. This is all piped into A stripped Refrigerator for an FC.<br /></blockquote><br /><br />I would not recommend this.&nbsp; If you're seeing a fog, it means you've already reached 100% humidity and are <i>still</i> piping in moisture, which will saturate your substrate and prevent the loss of moisture that is such a major pinning trigger.&nbsp; You don't want to see a fog.&nbsp; <br /><br />You might want to try reducing humidity in the refrigerator to &lt;95%, and lay a sheet of wax paper over the substrates until pins form.&nbsp; Lift the paper regularly to fan out under it and replace when it gets soggy.&nbsp; Be sure to wrinkle up the paper and then flatten it back out again so air can penetrate underneath.<br /><br />In a closed environment such as the fridge you're using, a single cool mist running four to five minutes on the hour should supply more than enough humidity without the ultrasonic running at all.&nbsp; In fact a few trays of perlite should do the trick.&nbsp; Leave the door propped partly open for fresh air.<br />RR","title":"Re: Pinning Strategy Query: Evaporation with 100% RH."}}